{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17413369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17413369"},"attributes":{"position":16,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T08:08:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T08:08:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18907"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566935"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:51:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:51:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18907"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"18907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18907"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.1,0.2,0.16,0.37]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11640"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80143"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11640"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18907"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65420"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"3579"},{"type":"tags","id":"8819"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27383"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80143"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of intense itching and a rash over his trunk and limbs. He returned from two years of humanitarian work in rural Uganda four months ago. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are hyperpigmented, lichenified patches on his trunk and limbs with scattered papules. Slit lamp examination reveals microfilariae in the anterior chamber of his eye. Skin snips confirm the presence of microfilariae.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Praziquantel","Doxycycline monotherapy","Albendazole monotherapy","Diethylcarbamazine","Ivermectin"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of onchocerciasis (river blindness), caused by infection with the parasitic worm \u003Cem\u003EOnchocerca volvulus\u003C/em\u003E. Infected blackflies bite humans to transmit the filarial worm, and are more common in areas around rivers or agricultural land.  The microfilariae travel as adult filariae in the subcutaneous tissue and in the eyes leading to the rash and eye symptoms.  Females worms may be up to 50cm in length. Patients may also present with lymphdenopathy, acute papular eruptions, intensely itchy rashes, and subcutaneous nodules (onchocercomato in which multiple worms may reside).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis is supported by his history of living in an endemic area (predominately sub-Saharan Africa, Brazil and Yemen), characteristic skin manifestations, and the presence of microfilariae in both skin snips and the anterior chamber of the eye.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIvermectin\u003C/strong\u003E is the drug of choice for onchocerciasis. It effectively kills the microfilariae and suppresses their production by adult worms. It is typically given as a single oral dose of 150 \u03bcg/kg every 6-12 months until the adult worms die (which may take 15 years). Ivermectin has a good safety profile and is well-tolerated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiethylcarbamazine\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in onchocerciasis as it can cause severe reactions, including exacerbation of ocular disease, due to massive microfilarial die-off. This reaction, known as the Mazzotti reaction, can be dangerous and potentially sight-threatening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPraziquantel\u003C/strong\u003E is not effective against onchocerciasis. It is primarily used to treat schistosomiasis and other trematode infections. While parasitic infections may co-exist in endemic areas, praziquantel would not address this patient\u0027s current infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlbendazole\u003C/strong\u003E alone has limited efficacy against onchocerciasis. While it may have some effect on adult worms when given for extended periods, it is not recommended as monotherapy. It may be used in combination with other agents in some cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E targets the endosymbiotic bacteria (\u003Cem\u003EWolbachia\u003C/em\u003E) within the adult worms and can lead to worm sterility and death when given for 4-6 weeks. However, it is not the first-line treatment and is typically reserved for special situations or used as adjunct therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ivermectin is the first-line treatment for onchocerciasis, given as a single oral dose every 6-12 months.","Onchocerciasis typically presents with intense pruritus, skin changes, and ocular symptoms in endemic regions.","Travel history to endemic regions (particularly sub-Saharan Africa) is crucial in diagnosis of onchocerciasis."],"references":["Centre of Disease Control. Treatment of Onchocerciasis. In: Centre of Disease Control (online). https://www.cdc.gov/filarial-worms/treatment/onchocerciasis.html. (Accessed January 2025)","Udall D. Recent Updates on Onchocerciasis: Diagnosis and Treatment. Clinical Infectious Disease. 2007: 44 (1). Available at: https://academic.oup.com/cid/article/44/1/53/433399"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65420"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18907"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65420"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-17T19:33:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-17T19:34:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11640"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80143"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id"